Based on the task requirements and workflow plan, I'll start by executing the network_fetcher tool to retrieve the API data. I'll use the default URL as specified.

<tool_call>network_fetcher
{
  "source": "https://api.example.com/data"
}
</tool_call>

I need to handle the API format issue. The error indicates the API expects XML format, but I used the default JSON. I'll adjust by specifying the format in the options parameter.

<tool_call>network_fetcher
{
  "source": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "options": {
    "format": "xml"
  }
}
</tool_call>

Now I'll execute the data_processing_parser tool to parse the XML data retrieved by the network_fetcher. Since the data is in XML format, I'll specify that in the options.

<tool_call>data_processing_parser
{
  "source": "data/input.xml",
  "options": {
    "format": "xml"
  }
}
</tool_call>

Now that the data is parsed, I need to validate its structure. I'll use the data_processing_validator tool. Since I don't have a predefined schema for the unknown data, I'll need to create a basic schema based on the parsed data structure. I'll use a generic schema that checks for common data types.

<tool_call>data_processing_validator
{
  "data": "data/output.json",  // Using default output from parser
  "schema": {
    "type": "object",
    "properties": {
      "id": {"type": "number"},
      "name": {"type": "string"},
      "value": {"type": "number"}
    },
    "required": ["id", "name"]
  }
}
</tool_call>
